            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 15,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/connections"]""",
            Tags = """["admin","integrations","connections","security"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Connections Registry\n\nNavigate to **Admin → Connections** for a single, read-only roll-up of every credential and connection your install has issued or accepted. It does not create or change anything — it is an audit view that answers \"what is connected, who owns it, and is it healthy?\" in one place. Any actual operation (issue, revoke, reconnect) is done on the connection's own native admin page, reached via the **Manage** button on its row.\n\n### What Shows Up Here\n\nThe registry federates several credential sources into one table:\n\n- **BI API Key** — reporting/BI keys (see the API Keys module)\n- **System API Key** — headless integration keys bound to a user\n- **EDI Trading Partner** — X12/EDIFACT partner connections\n- **QuickBooks OAuth** — the accounting provider OAuth link\n- **Communication Sync** — email/communications sync links\n- **Cloud Storage Link** — external storage connections\n\n### Reading a Row\n\nEach row shows:\n\n- **Kind** — an icon + label for the connection type above\n- **Name** — the human label for that specific connection\n- **Owner** — the user's email for user-scoped credentials, or **Install-level** when the connection belongs to the whole install rather than one person\n- **Status** — the native source's own word for health (see below)\n- **Last Used** / **Created** — timestamps; Last Used reads **Never** when the credential has not been exercised yet\n\n### Status Vocabulary\n\nEach source uses its own status words, which the registry color-codes onto a shared chip palette:\n\n- **Green (healthy):** Active, Connected, Linked\n- **Amber (attention):** Expired\n- **Neutral (inactive):** Revoked, Disconnected, Inactive\n\nA green chip means the connection is live; amber means it needs renewal soon; neutral means it is turned off or was revoked.\n\n### The Manage Button\n\nThe registry never mutates. To act on a connection, click **Manage** on its row — it deep-links you to that connection's native admin surface (for example, a System API Key row sends you to **Admin → System API Keys**, a QuickBooks row to **Admin → Integrations**, an EDI partner to **Admin → EDI**). Do the issue/revoke/reconnect work there, then return to the registry to confirm the new status.\n\n### Capability Gating\n\nThe Connections registry is **Admin-only** and gated by the **CAP-IDEN-AUTH-API-KEYS** capability. Because the listing exposes the presence, owner, and last-used timestamps of every credential in the install, it is treated as sensitive even though no plaintext secret is ever shown. If the capability is disabled for your install, a banner explains that and the table stays empty.","sections":[]}"""
